          }
        ],
        "title": "See also"
      },
      {
        "blocks": [
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "The methods to estimate the optimal number of bins are well founded\nin literature, and are inspired by the choices R provides for\nhistogram visualisation. Note that having the number of bins\nproportional to "
              },
              {
                "kind": "math",
                "latex": "n^{1/3}"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " is asymptotically optimal, which is\nwhy it appears in most estimators. These are simply plug-in methods\nthat give good starting points for number of bins. In the equations\nbelow, "
              },
              {
                "kind": "math",
                "latex": "h"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " is the binwidth and "
              },
              {
                "kind": "math",
                "latex": "n_h"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " is the number of\nbins. All estimators that compute bin counts are recast to bin width\nusing the "
              },
              {
                "external_url": "",
                "href": "/docs/api/ops/ptp",
                "kind": "link",
                "target": "ptp",
                "text": "ptp"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " of the data. The final bin count is obtained from\n"
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "we.round(we.ceil(range / h))"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": ". The final bin width is often less\nthan what is returned by the estimators below."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "items": [
              {
                "blocks": [
                  {
                    "inline": [
                      {
                        "kind": "text",
                        "text": "A compromise to get a good value. For small datasets the Sturges\nvalue will usually be chosen, while larger datasets will usually\ndefault to FD.  Avoids the overly conservative behaviour of FD\nand Sturges for small and large datasets respectively.\nSwitchover point is usually "
                      },
                      {
                        "kind": "math",
                        "latex": "a.size \\approx 1000"
                      },
                      {
                        "kind": "text",
                        "text": "."
                      }
                    ],
                    "type": "paragraph"
                  }
                ],
                "term_inline": [
                  {
                    "kind": "text",
                    "text": "'auto' (minimum bin width of the 'sturges' and 'fd' estimators)"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ],
            "type": "definition_list"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "'fd' (Freedman Diaconis Estimator)"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "formulas": [
              "h = 2 \\frac{IQR}{n^{1/3}} The binwidth is proportional to the interquartile range (IQR) and inversely proportional to cube root of a.size. Can be too conservative for small datasets, but is quite good for large datasets. The IQR is very robust to outliers."
            ],
            "type": "math_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "'scott'"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "formulas": [
              "h = \\sigma \\sqrt[3]{\\frac{24 \\sqrt{\\pi}}{n}} The binwidth is proportional to the standard deviation of the data and inversely proportional to cube root of ``x.size``. Can be too conservative for small datasets, but is quite good for large datasets. The standard deviation is not very robust to outliers. Values are very similar to the Freedman-Diaconis estimator in the absence of outliers."
            ],
            "type": "math_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "'rice'"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "formulas": [
              "n_h = 2n^{1/3} The number of bins is only proportional to cube root of ``a.size``. It tends to overestimate the number of bins and it does not take into account data variability."
            ],
            "type": "math_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "'sturges'"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "formulas": [
              "n_h = \\log _{2}(n) + 1 The number of bins is the base 2 log of ``a.size``.  This estimator assumes normality of data and is too conservative for larger, non-normal datasets. This is the default method in R's ``hist`` method."
            ],
            "type": "math_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "'doane'"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "formulas": [
              "n_h = 1 + \\log_{2}(n) + \\log_{2}\\left(1 + \\frac{|g_1|}{\\sigma_{g_1}}\\right)",
              "g_1 = mean\\left[\\left(\\frac{x - \\mu}{\\sigma}\\right)^3\\right]",
              "\\sigma_{g_1} = \\sqrt{\\frac{6(n - 2)}{(n + 1)(n + 3)}}",
              "An improved version of Sturges' formula that produces better estimates for non-normal datasets. This estimator attempts to account for the skew of the data."
            ],
            "type": "math_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "'sqrt'"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "formulas": [
              "n_h = \\sqrt n The simplest and fastest estimator. Only takes into account the data size."
            ],
            "type": "math_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Additionally, if the data is of integer dtype, then the binwidth will never\nbe less than 1."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          }
        ],
        "title": "Notes"
      },
      {
        "blocks": [
          {
            "lines": [
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "import whest as we"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "arr = we.array([0, 0, 0, 1, 2, 3, 3, 4, 5])"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "we.histogram_bin_edges(arr, bins='auto', range=(0, 1))"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "array([0.  , 0.25, 0.5 , 0.75, 1.  ])"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "we.histogram_bin_edges(arr, bins=2)"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "array([0. , 2.5, 5. ])"
              }
            ],
            "type": "doctest_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "For consistency with histogram, an array of pre-computed bins is\npassed through unmodified:"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "lines": [
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "we.histogram_bin_edges(arr, [1, 2])"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "array([1, 2])"
              }
            ],
            "type": "doctest_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "This function allows one set of bins to be computed, and reused across\nmultiple histograms:"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "lines": [
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "shared_bins = we.histogram_bin_edges(arr, bins='auto')"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "shared_bins"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "array([0., 1., 2., 3., 4., 5.])"
              }
            ],
            "type": "doctest_block"
          },
          {
            "lines": [
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "group_id = we.array([0, 1, 1, 0, 1, 1, 0, 1, 1])"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "hist_0, _ = we.histogram(arr[group_id == 0], bins=shared_bins)"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "hist_1, _ = we.histogram(arr[group_id == 1], bins=shared_bins)"
              }
            ],
            "type": "doctest_block"
          },
          {
            "lines": [
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "hist_0; hist_1"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "array([1, 1, 0, 1, 0])"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "array([2, 0, 1, 1, 2])"
              }
            ],
            "type": "doctest_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Which gives more easily comparable results than using separate bins for\neach histogram:"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "lines": [
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "hist_0, bins_0 = we.histogram(arr[group_id == 0], bins='auto')"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "hist_1, bins_1 = we.histogram(arr[group_id == 1], bins='auto')"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "hist_0; hist_1"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "array([1, 1, 1])"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "array([2, 1, 1, 2])"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "bins_0; bins_1"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "array([0., 1., 2., 3.])"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "array([0.  , 1.25, 2.5 , 3.75, 5.  ])"
              }
            ],
            "type": "doctest_block"
          }
        ],
        "title": "Examples"
      }
    ]
